16. What is Duel Wield and how does it work?<br>
<br>
Duel Wield (or DW for short) is the ability to use 2 1 handed weapons at the same time. Until you get DW you can not equip the Shield of the Slain Unicorn. The skill for warriors caps at 200. One of the few formulas that Verant has release for the combat system your chance to successfully DW is (level + skill)/600. <br>
<br>
Our current understanding of DW is that every delay of the off hand (or delay/10 seconds) the server checks your DW skill. If the check is successful then a regular to hit check is made. The weapon in your primary hand has no effect on the off hand. Stats have no effect on the chance to DW. Double Attack checks are made for the off hand when you get that skill.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
 <p>Wippin Blades - <i>Alat-Seldi</i><br>
Little Guy at the Big Kid's Table</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucharlam00.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Charlam00</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Guardian of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 754<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/10/01 2:46:11 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dual Wield</span><hr size=1> &quot;Nonetheless, you see a lot of twink monks with a fighting baton and essensce of dol. I guarantee every one of them you see will have the dol in their left hand (higher damage weapon).&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, that and it's Secondary slot only <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Prime hand gets a damage bonus added to each swing, one of the reason the insanely low delay weaps from Kunark got nerfed (moss covered twig, 3/10, now offhand ONLY).<br>
<br>
Basically you want lowest delay in prime hand, best dam/del ratio in offhand (wish wurmslayer were secondary equippable <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ), however you may also want to monkey with weapons a bit to manage agro more effectively as well.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubeatrixmaledicta.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Beatrix Maledicta</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot <img src=http://www.brellserilis.net/images/goldstartr.gif align=middle></span><br>  Posts: 134<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/10/01 4:41:21 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dual Wield</span><hr size=1> I agree with Wippin. The game runs a skill check on your offhand based on your dual wield skill regardless of what happens with your main hand swings. If the skill check succeeds there is a check to see if you hit. There is also a check to see if you double attack with the offhand, just as with the main hand.<br>
<br>
The reason why the fastest of two weapons should go into main hand is that you will get a dmg bonus in the main hand, starting with a modest +1 in the upper lvl 20s and then slowly increasing through the levels. The damage bonus indirectly alters the ratio on your weapon since you are in effect doing more damage than the weapon ratio implies.<br>
<br>
lower dly -&gt; more hits/min -&gt; dmg bonus applied more times per minute -&gt; some extra dmg/min.<br>
<br>
So provided you will use the faster of two weapons anyway, you may as well put it in your main hand to benefit from some extra dmg because of the bonus. The faster the weapon, the more total bonus dmg/min. In the offhand you dont get a bonus, so all that matters there is the ratio. The better the ratio, the more dmg/min.<br>
<br>
Theoretically, it is not necessarily true that lowest dly should always go into main though. Let's say you own a slower weapon with a fantastic ratio and a faster weapon with a horrible ratio. Putting the slow weapon in offhand could mean giving up too much dmg output provided your dual wield skill is low, since you will then fail most dual wield skill checks. It would be better to put the fast weapon in the offhand as it won't be doing much dmg either way because of its poor ratio. That's just a highly hypothetical example, though, to illustrate the mechanics of dual wield. The differences between the weapons would have to be extreme and you would have to have very low DW skill for this to hold.<br>
<br>
A final note: If you want to raise your dual wield skill rather than maximize dmg output, you put the faster weapon in the offhand to get more chances per minute for skill checks -&gt; less time needed to raise skill.<br>
 <p><b>Beatrix Maledicta</b><br>
