<img src="http://medlem.tripodnet.nu/beatrix_maledicta/Beatrix3.jpg" border="0"><br>




</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ulorddjim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lord Djim</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 34<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/10/01 9:13:31 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dual Wield</span><hr size=1> First off -- Dual weild. The easiest way to view this is your primary hand atttacks every time it possibly can.<br>
<br>
Your secondary hand attacks aproximately <br>
(level+Dual wield)/600 of the time.( I am iffy on the exact formula, but that is close.)  This means that if you are level 25 with a dual weild of 75 you will attack aproximately 1 time in 6 with the secondary hand. Your secondary hand will never get anywhere near your primary hand's speed.<br>
<br>
<br>
-- How to choose what weapon goes where. There are exceptions to these rules due to procs, hate managment issues, and just general weirdness, but these are good general rules<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1) If you are less than L1-L27 put the best ratio weapon in your primary hand, and the other weapon in your secondary.<br>
<br>
2)Once you are L28  you start getting a primary hand damage bonus of (level-25)/3 rounded down. At this point you do some comparisons. Which ever weapon gives the best ratio in the primary hand you put there, and the other goes in the secondary.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
 ( e.g. I have a  6/25 weapon and an 8/32 weapon<br>
 <br>
while I am  L1-27 <br>
8/32 primary, 6/25 secondary<br>
<br>
L28-30 I have a choice either:<br>
9/32 primary, 6/25 secondary<br>
or <br>
7/25 primary,8/32 secondary<br>
so I keep the slower weapon in the primary hand. ( 9/32&gt;7/25)<br>
<br>
L31-34  10/32 primary, 6/25 secondary or 8/25 primary, 8/32 secondary.  At this point and for all levels beyond the faster weapon is superior to the slower -- because  (8/25 &gt;10/32) <br>
In addition the faster weapon will improve faster as you level.)<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
These simple rules should serve you well until you get to very high level, and even then are good rules of thumb.<br>
